[3] Ghana, Brong-Ahafo and Volta regions
Date: Sat 4 Jun 2016
Source: Joy Online [edited]
http://www.myjoyonline.com/news/2016/June-4th/yellow-fever-strikes-in-brong-ahafo-volta-regions.php


[The Ghana Health Service issued the following press release:]

Confirmed Cases of Yellow Fever (YF) -- Brong-Ahafo and Volta Regions
---------------------------------------------------------------------
Over the past 4 weeks, the Ghana Health Service has received reports of confirmed yellow fever (YF) cases from the Brong-Ahafo and Volta regions. A total of 4 cases with no deaths have been reported.

[Of these,] 3 are from Jaman South district in the Brong-Ahafo region and one from Central Tongu district in the Volta Region.

There is no need to panic as the cases are confined to a few communities in the aforementioned districts, and previous widespread vaccination in 2011 in those districts provided most people with immunity against yellow fever.

Signs and Symptoms of Yellow Fever
Yellow fever is a viral hemorrhagic disease. It causes bleeding which may come out from any of the body openings (e.g.: the nose, mouth, bloody stools, vomiting blood at the end stage). The symptoms may also include fever with jaundice in the early stages and with multiple organ dysfunctions resulting in kidney and liver failure.

Treatment
Treatment is mostly symptomatic.

Mode of Spread
Spread is through the bite of infected _Aedes_ mosquitoes.

Preventive Measures
1. Prevention is by vaccination -- The vaccine is very effective. One injection of the vaccine protects one for life.
2. Avoidance and protection against mosquito bites.

Containment Measures and Response Actions Done
1. Public education on signs, symptoms and prevention.
2. Yellow fever vaccination coverage in the affected districts has been assessed and found to be high in those districts. Preventive vaccination coverage was done in the affected communities in 2011 and yellow fever vaccination protects one for life.
3. Planned selective reactive mop up vaccination in the affected communities/sub-districts.
4. Alert sent to all regions and nearby districts of the affected areas.
5. Surveillance has been enhanced across the country.

Way Forward
The risk of further transmission is low due to high yellow fever vaccination coverage in routine EPI and previous preventive vaccination campaign. However, we need to sustain enhanced surveillance, intensive public education of the disease, preventive measures and what to do if one suspects yellow fever.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[It is not clear if the containment measures listed above have been implemented already. A delay of 4 weeks or more could provide ample time for continued ongoing transmission of the yellow fever (YF) virus if there are unvaccinated individuals in these 2 localities. The proportion of individuals in these areas who are unvaccinated is not mentioned. The reason for delaying official reporting for 4 weeks is not given. It is not clear if these cases are spill-over from the sylvan (forest) cycle of transmission, are imported from elsewhere, or are locally acquired cases from the urban transmission cycle. One hopes that these are isolated cases, and do not represent the beginning of another African YF outbreak.

A map showing the locations of these 2 regions in central Ghana can be accessed at http://www.nationsonline.org/oneworld/map/ghana_map.htm. - Mod.TY]
